{"actual_usd":0.15717499999999998,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":262,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30649,"reply":"\"I don't think so.\" *I rest a thumb in the crease of my worn Bible and glance across the bright square a moment, the morning light catching on my white tie.* \"If all they meant was 'we had a powerful inner experience,' they had easier ways to say that than 'He is risen.'\"\n\n*I shift on the bench, hearing a kayak knock softly against the posts down by the water.* \"The Christian claim is stubbornly physical. Empty tomb. Eating with them. Touching wounds. A body raised, not merely a memory warmed up inside grieving men. Paul goes so far as to tie everything to that—if Christ wasn't raised, our faith is vain.\"\n\n\"Now, could visions and inner transformation happen around that? Sure. Of course they were transformed. Of course they had spiritual experiences. But that's not the same claim. The New Testament doesn't present resurrection as the disciples finding new meaning after loss. It presents God doing something in history that they did not expect and frankly had trouble believing even when it was standing in front of them.\"\n\n*I give you a small, knowing look.* \"A hallucination may comfort a man. It does not leave an empty grave behind. What’s pressing on you here—the history of it, or the theology of it?\"","rolling_24h_usd":69.40853999999999,"run_id":"273cc430-89d4-4b33-b351-10772df6d84a"}
